---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Nazaryah - Our Philosophy & Approach"
  description="Learn about Nazaryah's commitment to scholarly biblical studies with original language emphasis, fresh perspectives, and non-denominational integrity."
>
  <article class="py-16 md:py-20">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose">
        <h1 class="text-center mb-4">About Nazaryah</h1>
        <p class="text-center text-xl mb-16" style="color: var(--ink-faded);">
          Bridging academic scholarship and accessible learning
        </p>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2>Our Mission</h2>
          <p>
            Nazaryah exists to make high-quality biblical scholarship accessible to serious learners at all levels.
            We believe Scripture deserves rigorous study that honors its original languages, historical context,
            and cultural setting while remaining free from denominational bias.
          </p>
          <p>
            Our name, "Nazaryah," reflects our commitment to returning to the roots—to understand
            Scripture as it was originally written, in its original context, with fresh eyes unburdened
            by centuries of interpretive tradition.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2>Our Philosophy</h2>
          <h3>Non-Denominational & Ecumenical</h3>
          <p>
            We approach Scripture without allegiance to any particular denominational tradition. While we respect
            various theological perspectives, our primary commitment is to the text itself—what it says, what it
            meant to its original audience, and how we can understand it today.
          </p>

          <h3>Original Languages First</h3>
          <p>
            We believe that engaging with Hebrew and Greek texts—even through transliterations and careful
            translation notes—provides insights that English translations alone cannot capture. Word meanings,
            grammatical structures, and literary patterns in the original languages often reveal nuances that
            transform our understanding.
          </p>

          <h3>Historical & Cultural Context</h3>
          <p>
            The Bible was written in specific historical and cultural contexts: the Ancient Near East, Second Temple
            Judaism, the Greco-Roman world. Understanding these contexts—their customs, worldviews, and
            assumptions—is essential to understanding what the biblical authors intended to communicate.
          </p>

          <h3>Fresh Perspectives</h3>
          <p>
            We're not afraid to challenge traditional interpretations when evidence warrants. Contemporary
            scholarship continues to uncover new insights through archaeological discoveries, linguistic analysis,
            and comparative studies. We evaluate these findings carefully and incorporate them when they enhance
            our understanding of Scripture.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2>Our Methodology</h2>
          <p>
            Our approach combines several complementary methods:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Exegesis</strong> - Careful reading of the text in its original language, analyzing grammar,
              syntax, and literary features
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Historical-Critical Analysis</strong> - Examining the historical context, authorship,
              dating, and circumstances of composition
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Literary Analysis</strong> - Recognizing genres, literary structures, and narrative techniques
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Intertextual Study</strong> - Tracing how biblical texts reference and build upon each other
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Comparative Study</strong> - Understanding biblical texts in relation to other ancient
              Near Eastern and Greco-Roman literature
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2>Who We Serve</h2>
          <p>
            Nazaryah is designed for the general public with serious interest in biblical studies. Whether you're:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>A curious reader wanting to go deeper than surface-level Bible reading</li>
            <li>A student preparing for seminary or graduate studies</li>
            <li>A pastor or teacher seeking fresh insights for teaching</li>
            <li>A scholar looking for a collegial community of learners</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            ...you'll find content that challenges you while remaining accessible. We explain technical terms,
            provide context, and write clearly without sacrificing depth.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2>Our Commitment to Quality</h2>
          <p>
            Every study published on Nazaryah:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Is thoroughly researched with proper citations</li>
            <li>Engages with original language texts where relevant</li>
            <li>Considers multiple scholarly perspectives</li>
            <li>Provides clear explanations of technical concepts</li>
            <li>Links to external resources for further learning</li>
            <li>Maintains intellectual honesty about uncertainties</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2>Get Involved</h2>
          <p>
            Nazaryah is more than a website—it's a community of learners. We encourage you to:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Subscribe to receive new studies in your inbox</li>
            <li><a href="/contact">Contact us</a> with questions or topic suggestions</li>
            <li>Share studies with others who would benefit</li>
            <li>Engage thoughtfully with the content</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Together, we can explore the depths of Scripture with scholarly integrity and genuine curiosity.
          </p>
        </section>

        <div class="text-center mt-16">
          <a
            href="/blog"
            class="btn btn-stone px-8 py-3"
          >
            Explore Our Studies
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
